    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A planetary conjunction is when two or more planets appear to be close together in the sky, but it's not a collision, as the planets are actually at vast distances from each other. This phenomenon occurs when the Earth passes between the Sun and a planet, or when two planets are on the same side of the Sun, making them appear close to each other in the sky. It's a bit like when a group of goblins are clustered together in a cave, but they're not actually touching each other – they're just close enough to make it look like they're together. The reason we don't see them actually touching is that the planets are so far apart, even when they appear close, that their actual distances are still millions or billions of kilometers.",
