      "beast_suffix": "",
      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got carried away with the goblin analogy. To explain orbital inclination, think of it like this: imagine a group of goblins standing on a hill, each one representing a planet. Normally, they're all standing side by side, but one of them is tilted at an angle, so it's not directly in line with the others. This tilt affects how close the goblin appears to be to the others, even if it's actually at the same distance. The tilt of the orbits, or the inclination, is the angle between a planet's orbit and the plane of the Earth's orbit around the Sun. This inclination can cause the planets to appear closer or farther apart than they actually are, depending on their positions in their orbits. For example, when a planet is at its closest point to the Sun (perihelion), it appears closer to the Sun and Earth, even if it's not actually closer.",
      "source": "target",
